As an [[List of academic disciplines|academic discipline]] the study of '''politics in education''' has two main roots.  The first root is based on theories from [[political science]] while the second root is footed in [[Organizational studies|organizational theory]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Scribner|first=J. D.|author2=Aleman, E. |author3=Maxcy, B. |title=Emergence of the Politics of Education Field: Making Sense of the Messy Center|journal=Educational Administration Quarterly|date=February 1, 2003|volume=39|issue=1|pages=10–40|doi=10.1177/0013161X02239759}}</ref>    Political science attempts to explain how societies and [[social organization]]s use [[Political power|power]] to establish regulations and allocate resources.  Organizational theory uses [[scientific theories]] of management to develop deeper understandings regarding the function of organizations.

Researchers have drawn a distinction between two types of politics in [[school]]s.  The term ''micropolitics'' refers to the use of formal and informal power by individuals and groups to achieve their goals in organizations. Cooperative and conflictive processes are integral components of micropolitics. ''Macropolitics'' refers to how power is used and decision making is conducted at district, state, and federal levels.  Macropolitics is generally considered to exist outside the school, but researchers have noted that micro- and macropolitics may exist at any level of school systems depending on circumstance.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Blasé |first=J. |author2=Blase, J.|title=The Micropolitics of Instructional Supervision: A Call for Research |journal=Educational Administration Quarterly |date=February 1, 2002|volume=38|issue=1|pages=6–44|doi=10.1177/0013161X02381002}}</ref>

There exist significant difference between "Politics of Education" and "Politics in Education". More debates on the preavailing differences are solicited from academia of the world to define politics educationally.

